data.text: @spirillen_der Background noise raises along with more fluctuation. But other than that the curve is the same. Think of it as pixels in an image of say, a tree. Each measurement makes the WHOLE image clearer. Not just a single spot. But how many details you can see.

@NorsemanAnon @spirillen_der @micheelsen Det man skulle fokusere på, og som også er gammel viden. Sundt immunforsvar som du siger - Og det eneste der skal gøres ifm. "lockdown" - er for at følge presset på Hospitals-indlæggelser, om presset bliver for stort. Hvilket det aldrig har været. Kun i hovederne på Brostrøm.

@spirillen_der @micheelsen It simply doesn't. 

There's nothing we can do about these things. Except trying to maximise our own immune systems. That's all. Which already is a huge truth.
@micheelsen Awesome. How does it affect the curve when a country stops mass testing in the middle of a surge?
@spirillen_der My algorithem is fractal so it doesn’t care about mass volumn.
@micheelsen Sweden stopped mass testing a while back. That’s probably the main reason why they see a much lower infection rate.
